observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
a.) Instruct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (MDRRM) Officer and all other implementing offices to implement all projects funded by the LDRRMF based on the target timelines indicated in the MDRRM Plan to ensure optimal utilization of the fund so that the services and benefits from these projects are delivered to the constituents without unnecessary delay and to equip the municipality against the adverse impacts of disaster or calamity;
(Other subpoints and actions as previously recommended.)

We reiterated the following recommendation that the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant:
a. Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
b. Impose the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions to all employees who could not settle their cash advances after demand letters were issued to them as provided for under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to do the following:
a. Assign an adequate number of members that will compose the Inventory Committee and temporarily relieve them of their regular duties to the conduct of the physical inventory taking until completion of the activity;
b. The Inventory Committee strictly comply with the procedural guidelines stated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fast track the completion of the conduct of the physical count of PPE by determining the properties found at the station, missing or non-existing PPEs, and the condition of the property items whether serviceable or not, and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly approved Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment of all properties owned by the Municipality;
c. The MAO and GSO undertake and complete the procedures under Items 6.3.1 and 6.3.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
d. Property and Accounting Units shall undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:
a. The Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of the PPE including identification of on-going projects recorded under the CIP accounts and determination of non-existing PPE or Infrastructure Projects;
b. The Engineering Office to coordinate with the Accounting Office regarding the status of the CIP projects and determine prior years’ completed projects not transferred to the appropriate PPE accounts;
c. The Municipal Accountant take up necessary adjusting entries to adjust the CIP accounts based on the Certificates of Project Completion and Acceptance submitted by the CEO; and
d. The Municipal Accountant take up necessary adjusting entries to drop from the books of accounts the lumped amount shown as beginning balances without details under the CIP accounts after the Inventory Committee has confirmed the non-existence of these balances to present reliable balances of the CIP accounts in the books.

1.13 We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to do the following:

a. Assign an adequate number of members that will compose the Inventory Committee and temporarily relieve them of their regular duties to devote their full time to the conduct of the physical inventory taking until completion of the activity;

b. The Inventory Committee strictly comply with the procedural guidelines stated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fast track the completion of the conduct of the physical count of PPE by determining the properties found at the station, missing or non-existing PPEs, and the condition of the property items whether serviceable or not, and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly approved Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment of all properties owned by the Municipality;

c. The MAO and GSO undertake and complete the procedures under Items 6.3.1 and 6.3.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

d. Property and Accounting Units shall undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.

2.10 We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:

a. The Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of the PPE including identification of on-going projects recorded under the CIP accounts and determination of non-existing PPE or Infrastructure Projects;

b. The Engineering Office to coordinate with the Accounting Office regarding the status of the CIP projects and determine prior years’ completed projects not transferred to the appropriate PPE accounts;

c. The Municipal Accountant take up necessary adjusting entries to adjust the CIP accounts based on the Certificates of Project Completion and Acceptance submitted by the CEO; and

d. The Municipal Accountant take up necessary adjusting entries to drop from the books of accounts the lumped amount shown as beginning balances without details under the CIP accounts after the Inventory Committee has confirmed the non-existence of these balances to present reliable balances of the CIP accounts in the books.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit List of Real Property Tax Delinquencies as of December 31, 2020 to determine the actual RPT/SET Receivable as basis in adjusting the abnormal balances;

Require the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit an updated Assessment Roll at the beginning of the year pursuant to Section 212 of RA No. 7160;  

Require the Municipal Accountant to establish in the books of GF and SEF:

•	the actual RPT/SET Receivables for prior years based on the List of Real Property Tax Delinquencies and to adjust the abnormal balances of the accounts; and 

•	the RPT/SET Receivables for the current year based on the updated Assessment Roll pursuant to the requirements of Section 19.b, Chapter 3 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, for fair presentation of the RPT/SET receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We reiterated the following recommendation that the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant:
Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Impose the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions to all employees who could not settle their cash advances after demand letters were issued to them as provided for under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Ensure that no additional cash advances be granted to those officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated               February 10, 1997; and
Closely coordinate with COA-ICFAU regarding the status of previously submitted liquidation documents or charges against previous years’ confidential fund so that said office could correspondingly issue a credit advice or credit notice.

